<h1> "W.Va. Businesses Regroup After Tap Water Is Restored" </h1>
    <p>RENEE MONTAGNE, HOST: </p>
    <p>More than half of the customers affected by last week's chemical leak in West Virginia now have access to safe tap water. About 300,000 people were told not to drink, wash or cook with water after the spill tainted the water supply. For days, the ban on tap water crippled the local economy.</p>
    <p>And as officials continue to lift the ban zone by zone, small businesses are showing signs of life once again. NPR's Hansi Lo Wang reports.</p>
    <p>(SOUNDBITE OF POURING CRUSHED ICE)</p>
